    "text": "Shortly after Ronald Reagan was elected president, former Federal Reserve Chairman Arthur Burns paid a visit to then-Fed Chairman Paul Volcker. Burns brought a warning: The president-elect’s advisers, led by Milton Friedman, wanted to replace the Fed chairman with a computer. He might have been biased, but Mr. Volcker opposed the idea that a complex monetary system should be governed by simple, mechanical rules, and the idea never caught on.\nDecades later the Fed remains unnecessarily unpredictable. The central bank’s new leadership... ",
